				<div class="elementor-element elementor-element-8c6b0ea bio elementor-widget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id="8c6b0ea" data-element_type="widget" data-widget_type="text-editor.default">
				<div class="elementor-widget-container">
					<div class="elementor-text-editor elementor-clearfix"><h2>BIO</h2>
Amélie Marian is a Professor in the <a href="https://www.cs.rutgers.edu/">Computer Science Department</a> at <a href="https://www.rutgers.edu/">Rutgers University</a>. Her research interests are in Accountability of Decision-making Systems, Transparent Digital Democracy, Explainable Rankings, Personal Digital Traces, and Data Integration. Amélie received her Ph.D. in Computer Science from <a href="https://www.cs.columbia.edu/">Columbia University</a> in 2005. from March 1999 to August 2000, Amélie was a member of the VERSO project at <a href="https://www.inria.fr/fr/centre-inria-de-paris">INRIA-Rocquencourt</a>. She received B.S. and M.S. degree from <a href="https://dauphine.psl.eu/">Université Paris Dauphine</a>, France in 1998 and 1999, respectively. She is the recipient of a Microsoft Live Labs Award (2006), three Google Research Awards (2008, 2010, and 2012) and an NSF CAREER award (2009).</div>
